Overview

This class covers empirical methods for language sciences. The main goal is for you to understand and take control of the full cycle of (linguistic) analysis: planning; collection; processing; exploration; visualization; and analysis. By contrast to previous classes, you will also be introduced to inferential statistics. We follow a model-centric and computational approach.

Analysis cycle

Inferential statistics

Methods to not only describe or summarize the observed data (descriptive statistics) but to generalize to unobserved data and make predictions.

Peer review (20%)

  • 2 in total

Mid-term exam (20%)

  • Submitted through Aula Global
  • Graded automatically
  • Single attempt

Analysis design and execution (40%)

  • A report of analysis designed and executed by yourself
  • If done in groups: A clear division of labor between members needs to be decided and approved
  • Hereâs a template: nn
  • Evaluation criteria (100 points max)
    • Clarity: the analysis is clearly and succintly described; appropriate use of visual devices (30 points)
    • Replicability: the analysis plan covers all steps to allow for its replication (15 points)
    • Content: the analysis is well motivated and executed using the appropriate techniques (40 points)
    • Reproduceability: the analysis provides all the material necessary to reproduce it (15 points)
    • Creativity: The analysis goes above and beyond in one or multiple dimensions: e.g., visual devices; research question; methodology; documentation (20 points)

Failing the âanalysis design and executionâ the first time entails saving the remainder activities with a 40% of value on the final grade. The mid-term exam will be recovered through another exam. The re-sit of the âanalysis design and executionâ will also be an exam."

Replicability and reproduceability

These terms are used differently âand sometimes interchangeablyâ across the literature. However, they tend to check most of the same boxes. We follow the National Academies of Sciences and Medicine (2019) and define them as:

  • Replicability: obtaining consistent results using the same input data; computational steps, methods, and code; and conditions of analysis

  • Reproduceability: obtaining consistent results across studies aimed at answering the same scientific question, each of which has obtained its own data

In all cases, documentation is key

R

We will use the programming language R. You do not need to have programmed neither in R nor any other language before. You also do not need to install R on your computer to follow the class: interactive notebooks have been set up so that everything can be executed from the cloud. That being said, I strongly recommend you to install R to get the most out of this class. Additionally, I also recommend installing RStudio. This is a graphical interface that allows you to manipulate R code & data more easily. You donât strictly need it, but chances are itâs going to make your quantitative life easier.

Installing R and RStudio

The details of how to install R and RStudio depend on your operating system. This Datacamp tutorial gives instructions on how to do so for Windows, Mac OS X, and Ubuntu.

Descriptive statistics review

Mean (finite case)

\[\Large \bar{x} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i} x_i\]

heights1 <- c(170,178,162,166,183,185) #a vector of heights in cms

(170 + 178 + 162 + 166 + 183 + 185) * (1 / 6) #calculating the mean explicitly

[1] 174
sum(heights1) * (1 / length(heights1)) #using sum() and length() functions

[1] 174
mean(heights1) #using the mean() function directly

[1] 174

Median (finite case)

If the number of observations is even and ordered: \[\Large median(X) = x_{\frac{n+1}{2}}\]

If odd and ordered: \[\Large median(X) = \frac{x_{n/2} + x_{(n/2)+1}}{2}\]

sort(heights1) #not necessary to compute median, just for illustration

[1] 162 166 170 178 183 185
median(heights1)

[1] 174
heights2 <- c(170,178,162,166,183,185,155) #a vector of heights in cms
sort(heights2) #not necessary to compute median, just for illustration

[1] 155 162 166 170 178 183 185
median(heights2)

[1] 170

More examples

heights3 <- c(170,178,162,166,183,185,188,300) #a vector of heights in cms
mean(heights3)

[1] 191.5
median(heights3)

[1] 180.5

Samples, populations, and estimates

set.seed(333)
#Let's let the computer generate the data
#We will simulate reaction times (in milliseconds)

#Starting small, sampling just 5 observations and telling R that the population's mean is 150 ms, with 40 ms of standard deviation

sim_reaction_times <- rnorm(n = 5, #number of samples
                            mean = 150, #mean of the normal distribution
                            sd = 40) #std. deviation of the normal distribution

sim_reaction_times #look at what reaction times we sampled

[1] 146.68753 227.38724  67.94841 161.10956  88.96158
hist(sim_reaction_times, #data we are plotting
     main = 'Simulated reaction times (small sample)', #title of our histogram
     xlab = 'Reaction time')  #Label of x-axis

mean(sim_reaction_times) #calculate their mean

[1] 138.4189
median(sim_reaction_times) #calculate their median

[1] 146.6875
#The same thing, but now with 1000 observations sampled

sim_reaction_times <- rnorm(n = 1000, mean = 150, sd = 20) #sample 1000 times from a Normal distribution with mean 150 and sd of 20
hist(sim_reaction_times) #visualize the reaction times we sampled

mean(sim_reaction_times) #calculate their mean

[1] 150.4272
median(sim_reaction_times) #calculate their median

[1] 149.6826
plot(density(sim_reaction_times))

#Changing the generating distribution
sim_reaction_times_g <- rgamma(n = 1000, shape=1, scale=150) #sample 1000 times from a Gamma distribution with mean 150 and sd of 20

hist(sim_reaction_times_g)

mean(sim_reaction_times_g)

[1] 155.7832
median(sim_reaction_times_g)

[1] 106.3779
plot(density(sim_reaction_times_g))

Variance & standard deviation

\[\Large \sigma_X = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i}^{n}(x_i - \bar{x})^2}\]

heights1

[1] 170 178 162 166 183 185
var(heights1)

[1] 88.4
sd(heights1) #the same as sqrt(var(heights))

[1] 9.402127
#Unpacking variance and standard deviation
x_bar <- mean(heights1) #we assign this number to a variable named x_bar
x_bar

[1] 174
dev_heights <- heights1 - x_bar #deviations of each height from the mean
dev_heights

[1]  -4   4 -12  -8   9  11
squared_dev_heights <- dev_heights**2 #squared deviations from the mean
squared_dev_heights

[1]  16  16 144  64  81 121
sum_squared_dev_heights <- sum(squared_dev_heights) #sum of the squared deviations
sum_squared_dev_heights

[1] 442
var_heights <- ( 1 / (length(heights1)-1) ) * sum_squared_dev_heights #divide by number of observations - 1
var_heights

[1] 88.4
sqrt(var_heights) #square root of the variance = std

[1] 9.402127
